[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] A presidential election was held in Massachusetts on December 18, 1788, and January 7, 1789, as part of the 1788–89 United States presidential election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Federalists led the polls in the first round of voting in each of the state's eight electoral districts.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The Massachusetts General Court subsequently chose one elector from among the leading candidates in each district and appointed two further electors to represent the state at-large.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] All 10 electors voted for George Washington and John Adams.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Federalists won the 1788 Massachusetts elections, re-electing the incumbent governor John Hancock and electing majorities in the Massachusetts Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Federalist legislators proceeded to divided the state into eight electoral districts, with each district choosing one elector in the upcoming presidential election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] While the district system paid lip service to democratic representation, the map adopted by the General Court was gerrymandered to overrepresent the Federalist-leaning counties in Eastern Massachusetts.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Washington was widely expected to be the first choice of the Electoral College in the first elections held under the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Some uncertainty persisted concerning the choice of the first vice president, however, due partly to the electoral system established by Article II of the Constitution.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Under this system, each elector voted for two candidates; the candidate with the largest majority was elected president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] With Washington likely to become president, many observers expected Adams to receive the other vote of most of the electors.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Some, such as Alexander Hamilton, feared Adams's popularity would be so great as to result in a tied vote, throwing the election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Hamilton believed this event would be deeply embarrassing to the new government and personally intervened with the electors to urge them not to vote for Adams.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] More than 200 candidates received votes in the first round.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Voters in each district voted for two candidates, with the two highest-placed candidates advancing to a runoff in the General Court.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The electors appointed by the General Court met on February 4, 1789, and voted for Washington and Adams.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Massachusetts chose eight electors from single-member districts and two additional electors to represent the state at-large.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Early election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The following table compares the sum of the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each township to give an approximate sense of the statewide popular vote.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The Massachusetts General Court met on January 7, 1789, to appoint two electors to represent the state at-large and eight electors to represent districts where no candidate won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] In the district races, the legislature chose between the two candidates with the most votes in the general election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The state's election law as originally written required the legislature to choose two at-large electors who had not been candidates in the general election, but the large number of candidates led legislators to drop this requirement.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the previous election, 6 Pro-Administration and 2 Anti-Administration Representatives had been elected.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] One representative, George Partridge (P) of the 5th district resigned August 14, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] His seat was vacant at the time of the 1790 elections, so that there were 5 Pro-Administration and 2 Anti-Administration incumbents, all of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Three candidates ran in districts with different numbers from the previous election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] It is not clear from the source used whether there was redistricting or if the districts had simply been renumbered.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Massachusetts law at the time required a majority for election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This occurred on the first ballot in the 1st, 2nd, 3rd and 4th districts.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the remaining four districts additional elections were required.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the 5th and 7th districts, a majority was achieved on the 2nd ballot.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In the 8th district, a majority was achieved on the 4th ballot, while in the 6th district, 9 ballots were required.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The first ballot was held on October 4, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Four representatives, from the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, and 4th districts won on the first ballot.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The second ballot was held in the 5th, 6th, 7th, and 8th districts on November 26, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The third ballot was held in the 6th and 8th districts on January 25, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Neither district achieved a majority on this ballot.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The fourth ballot was held in the 6th and 8th districts on April 4, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] A majority was achieved in the 8th district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The fifth ballot was held in the 6th district on September 8, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was the last ballot before the first session of the 2nd Congress began on October 24, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The 6th district was still vacant at the start of the 1st session.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The sixth ballot was held in the 6th district on November 11, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The seventh ballot was held in the 6th district on December 26, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The eighth ballot was held in the 6th district on December 26, 1791, during the 1st session of the 2nd Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-1792-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The ninth and final ballot was held in the 6th district on April 2, 1792, near the end of the 1st session of the 2nd Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-1793-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-massachusetts] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] A presidential election was held in Massachusetts between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] In this election, two Congressional districts chose five electors each, the remaining two districts chose three electors.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Each elector chosen by majority vote of voters in Congressional district.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] If an insufficient number of electors are chosen by majority vote from a Congressional district, remaining electors would be appointed by the state legislature.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] Massachusetts unanimously voted for independent candidate and incumbent president, George Washington.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-massachusetts] The total vote is composed of 20,343 for Federalist electors, all of whom were supportive of Washington.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election] A **special election** was held in **Massachusetts's 4th congressional district** August 24, 1801 to fill a vacancy caused by the resignation of Levi Lincoln Sr.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election] (DR) on March 5, 1801, before the first session of Congress, upon being appointed U.S.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election] Massachusetts electoral law required a majority for election, which was not met on the June 22, 1801 first ballot, requiring a second election held on August 24.
[src:1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election/1801-massachusetts-s-4th-congressional-district-special-election] Hastings took his seat on January 11, 1802.
